The '''Corantijn''', '''Corantijn''' or '''[[Courantyne River]]''' is the Border River between [[Suriname]] and [[Guyana]]. The '''Corantijn Basin''' is one of a number of archaeological sites located in the hinterland of [[Suriname]], [[South America]].<ref>{{cite web |author=Versteeg, Aad |year=2003 |url=http://www.surinaamsmuseum.net/suriname-voor-columbus/ |title='''Suriname before Columbus''' |publisher= Paramaribo: Stichting Surinaams Museum, Libri Musei Surinamensis 1. }}</ref> <ref>{{cite web |author=Renzo Duin and Cheryl White (eds.) |year=2017 |url=https://www.academia.edu/33505985/Archaeology_in_Suriname_Duin_and_White_2017_Edited_Volume_ |title='''Archaeology in Suriname''' |publisher=''His/HerTori: Tijdschrift voor Surinaamse Geschiedenis en Cultuur''. }}</ref> The Suriname archaeological sites provide information on Indigenous Peoples who lived in Suriname before 1492. Most of the [[petroglyphs]] are in the Corantijn Basin site. Petroglyphs provide an important insight into the ceremonial, mythical and religious world of these precontact indigenous peoples.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://home.planet.nl/~vrstg/guianas/suriname/rgdpaper.htm |title=The history of prehistoric archaeological research in Suriname |publisher= |accessdate=2007-04-03 }}</ref> <ref>{{cite web |author=Duin, Renzo |year=2017 |url=https://www.academia.edu/33588782/Written_in_Stone_Revisiting_Early_Studies_on_Timehri_Petroglyphs_in_Suriname_Duin_2017_ |title=Written in Stone: Revisiting Early Studies on Timehri Petroglyphs in Suriname |publisher=In "'''Archaeology in Suriname'''", '''''His/HerTori: Tijdschrift voor Surinaamse Geschiedenis en Cultuur'''''. Renzo Duin and Cheryl White (eds.). Pp. 57-72. Paramaribo: IMwO. |accessdate=2018-05-05 }}</ref>
The site is also well known as the habitat of [[Pseudoplatystoma]], a [[genus]] of several South American [[catfish]].<ref name=tigrinum>{{FishBase species|genus=Pseudoplatystoma|species = tigrinum|year=2007|month=Apr}}</ref>
